Document: Importing 3D Scenes
Path: godot/tutorials/assets_pipeline/importing_3d_scenes/advanced_import_settings.rst
Summary: This section details advanced import settings for 3D scenes in Godot.

When importing 3D scenes into Godot, several advanced settings allow for fine-tuning the import process. These settings are accessible through the Import dock in the Godot editor.

**General Settings:**

*   **Model:** This section contains general settings for the 3D model.
    *   **Mesh Compression:** Controls the level of compression applied to mesh data. Higher compression reduces file size but may slightly impact visual quality.
    *   **Use Placeholders:** If enabled, placeholders are used for imported meshes, which can speed up initial loading and iteration.
    *   **Invert Tangents:** Some 3D modeling software export tangents with different winding orders. This option allows you to correct for that.
    *   **Optimize Meshes:** This option attempts to optimize the mesh data for better performance.
    *   **Optimize Surfaces:** Similar to optimizing meshes, this optimizes individual surfaces within the mesh.
    *   **LOD Settings:** Allows configuration of Level of Detail (LOD) for the imported model, enabling different mesh versions to be displayed based on camera distance.

**Scene Settings:**

*   **Scene:** This section deals with settings related to the scene structure.
    *   **Generate Lightmap UVs:** If enabled, Godot will attempt to generate UV coordinates suitable for lightmapping. This is crucial for baked lighting.
    *   **Lightmap Tiling:** Controls the tiling of lightmap textures.
    *   **Lightmap Resolution:** Sets the resolution for generated lightmap UVs.
    *   **Lightmap Shrink:** Adjusts the margin between UV islands in the lightmap.
    *   **Scene Root Node:** Allows specifying a custom root node for the imported scene.

**Animation Settings:**

*   **Animation:** This section is for configuring imported animations.
    *   **Animation Compression:** Controls the compression applied to animation data.
    *   **Looping:** Enables or disables looping for imported animations.
    *   **Loop Start/End:** Defines the start and end frames for animation looping.
    *   **Root Motion:** If enabled, root motion data from the animation will be used for character movement.
    *   **Animation FPS:** Sets the frames per second for imported animations.

**Material Settings:**

*   **Material:** This section manages material import options.
    *   **Default Material:** Allows specifying a default material to be used if imported materials are missing or problematic.
    *   **Import Materials:** Enables or disables the import of materials from the source file.
    *   **Material Search/Override:** Options to control how Godot searches for and overrides materials.

**Texture Settings:**

*   **Texture:** This section pertains to imported textures.
    *   **Texture Compression:** Controls the compression method used for imported textures.
    *   **Mipmaps:** Enables or disables the generation of mipmaps for textures.
    *   **Texture Filter:** Sets the filtering mode for textures (e.g., nearest, linear).
    *   **Anisotropic Filtering:** Enables or disables anisotropic filtering for textures.

**Node Settings:**

*   **Node:** This section allows for specific node import configurations.
    *   **Node Conversion:** Options to convert specific node types during import.
    *   **Node Renaming:** Rules for renaming nodes during the import process.

By adjusting these advanced import settings, users can significantly optimize the performance, visual fidelity, and workflow of their 3D assets within the Godot Engine.
---CHUNK---
Document: Advanced Import Settings
Path: godot/tutorials/assets_pipeline/importing_3d_scenes/advanced_import_settings.rst
Summary: This section describes the advanced import settings for 3D models in Godot, focusing on per-object options, model previews, and animation previews.

The advanced import settings provide per-object options, model previews, and animation previews. To access these settings, select the Advanced... button at the bottom of the import dock. This functionality is available for 3D models imported as scenes and for animation libraries.

Note: This page focuses exclusively on options within the advanced import settings and does not cover general import dock options or other related topics. For information on those subjects, please refer to the Import Configuration page.
---CHUNK---
Document: Importing 3D Scenes
Path: godot/tutorials/assets_pipeline/importing_3d_scenes/advanced_import_settings.rst
Summary: This section describes the Scene tab in the Advanced Import Settings dialog, highlighting its 3D preview functionality.
The first tab you'll see is the Scene tab. The options available in the panel on the right are identical to the Import dock, but you have access to a 3D preview. The 3D preview can be rotated by holding down the left mouse button then dragging the mouse. Zoom can be adjusted using the mouse wheel.
