Document: Importing 3D Scenes
Path: godot/tutorials/assets_pipeline/importing_3d_scenes/advanced_import_settings.rst
Summary: This section details advanced import settings for individual nodes within a 3D scene, focusing on physics, navigation, and occlusion generation.

You can select individual nodes in the **Scene** tab of the import settings to configure per-node import options.

- **Skip Import:** If checked, the node will not be included in the final imported scene. This option disables all other settings for the selected node.
- **Generate > Physics:** If checked, a PhysicsBody3D parent node will be created, with collision shapes as siblings to the MeshInstance3D node.
- **Generate > NavMesh:** If checked, a NavigationRegion3D child node will be generated for navigation.
    - **Mesh + NavMesh:** Keeps the original mesh visible along with the navigation mesh.
    - **NavMesh Only:** Imports only the navigation mesh, without a visual representation. This is useful when a manually authored simplified mesh is used for navigation.
- **Generate > Occluder:** If checked, an OccluderInstance3D sibling node will be generated for occlusion culling, using the mesh's geometry as a basis.
    - **Mesh + Occluder:** Keeps the original mesh visible along with the occluder.
    - **Occluder Only:** Imports only the occluder, without a visual representation. This is useful when a manually authored simplified mesh is used for occlusion culling.

The following options are visible only when specific generation options are enabled:

- **Physics > Body Type:** (Visible if **Generate > Physics** is enabled) Determines the type of PhysicsBody3D to create:
    - **Static:** Creates a StaticBody3D.
    - **Dynamic:** Creates a RigidBody3D.
    - **Area:** Creates an Area3D.
- **Physics > Shape Type:** (Visible if **Generate > Physics** is enabled) Determines the collision shape type:
    - **Trimesh:** Provides precise per-triangle collision but can only be used with a Static body type. Recommended for static level geometry.
    - Other types: Less precise, may require manual configuration, and can be used with any body type. For dynamic geometry, use primitive shapes for better performance or convex decomposition for large, complex shapes.
- **Decomposition > Advanced:** (Visible if **Physics > Shape Type** is **Decompose Convex**) If checked, allows adjustment of advanced decomposition options. If disabled, only a preset **Precision** can be adjusted.
- **Decomposition > Precision:** (Visible if **Physics > Shape Type** is **Decompose Convex**) Controls the precision for convex decomposition. Higher values increase collision detail but also increase generation time and physics simulation CPU usage. Keep this value as low as possible for your use case to improve performance.
- **Occluder > Simplification Distance:** (Visible if **Generate > Occluder** is **Mesh + Occluder** or **Occluder Only**) Higher values reduce the occluder mesh's vertex count, decreasing CPU usage but potentially causing more occlusion culling issues (false positives/negatives). If objects disappear unexpectedly, try decreasing this value.
---CHUNK---
Document: Importing 3D Scenes
Path: godot/tutorials/assets_pipeline/importing_3d_scenes/advanced_import_settings.rst
Summary: This document details the advanced import settings for meshes and materials in Godot, explaining how to configure specific import options for individual assets.

Configuring mesh and material import options
In the Advanced Import Settings dialog, you can select individual meshes or materials by switching to the **Meshes** or **Materials** tab, or by unfolding options in the **Scene** tab's tree view.

Mesh Import Options:
- Save to File: Saves the Mesh resource to an external file (e.g., .res or .tres). This is useful for specific nodes like MeshInstance3D, MultiMeshInstance3D, GPUParticles3D, or CPUParticles3D, but not typically needed for instancing scenes. Using the .res extension is recommended for smaller file sizes and faster loading.
- Generate > Shadow Meshes: Overrides the scene-wide "Create Shadow Meshes" option. Options are Default, Enable, or Disable.
- Generate > Lightmap UV: Overrides the scene-wide "Light Baking" option. Options are Default, Enable, or Disable. Enabling this with "Static" light baking mode is equivalent to using "Static Lightmaps" for the mesh, and disabling it with "Static Lightmaps" is equivalent to using "Static" mode.
- Generate > LODs: Overrides the scene-wide "Generate LODs" option. Options are Default, Enable, or Disable.
- LODs > Normal Merge Angle: The minimum angle difference between vertices to preserve a geometry edge during LOD generation. Decreasing this value can help with visual issues but may reduce LOD generation efficiency.

Material Import Options:
- Use External: When checked and an output path is specified, this allows the use of an external material instead of the one included in the original 3D scene file.
---CHUNK---
Document: Importing 3D Scenes
Path: godot/tutorials/assets_pipeline/importing_3d_scenes/advanced_import_settings.rst
Summary: This section explains how to extract and modify materials from imported 3D scenes in Godot.

To modify materials authored in 3D modeling software within the Godot editor, you need to use external material resources. This is useful when you want to configure material features not supported by your 3D application, use different texture filtering modes, or replace existing materials with custom ones, such as those using a custom shader.

To extract materials, open the Advanced Import Settings dialog for your 3D scene. In the top-left corner, select Actions… > Extract Materials. You will then be prompted to choose a folder to save the extracted material `.tres` files. After confirming the extraction, Godot automatically configures the 3D scene to use these external material references.

Note: After extracting materials, the 3D scene automatically uses external material references, so you do not need to manually enable "Use External" on each material for the `.tres` file to be effective.

When "Use External" is enabled, the Advanced Import Settings dialog will continue to display the mesh's original materials from the 3D modeling software. Customizations made to the extracted materials will not be visible in this dialog. To preview your modified materials, you must place the imported 3D scene into another scene within the Godot editor.

Godot will not overwrite changes made to extracted materials upon reimporting the source 3D scene. However, if a material's name is changed in the source 3D file, the link between the original material and the extracted material will be broken. In such cases, you will need to use the Advanced Import Settings dialog to re-associate the renamed material with the existing extracted material. This can be done in the dialog's Materials tab by selecting the material, enabling "Save to File," and then specifying the save path using the "Path" option.
---CHUNK---
